Current The Human Realms and the Demon Marches (Present day)
Today, the former Vel’thorne territories are divided among fifteen human kingdoms and a dozen of poor grand duthies. Four of the Kingdoms and Two Grand Dutchies border the demonic lands directly, while the others lie farther north. Internal rivalries and shifting alliances among all fifteen kingdoms and grand dutchies are constant, and many fear that a new continental war between humans could erupt at any moment.
Smaller wars between kingdome, grand dutchies are more common then expected. "Private" internal wars between counties, baronies and sometimes even dutchies is constant considering the amount of noble territories.
Each kingdom and Grand Dutchy follows a classical feudal structure:

Duchy (Ruler: Duke) — The largest and most powerful feudal territories. Often nearly autonomous, containing multiple subordinate regions. Dukes are usually blood relatives of the monarch.
County (Ruler: Count) — The standard administrative division. Counts maintain order, collect taxes, and raise troops. They may answer to a duke or directly to the king.
Viscounty (Ruler: Viscount) — Often a deputy territory assisting a count, though some exist as independent holdings.
Barony (Ruler: Baron) — The basic land unit, ranging from single villages to clusters of manors.
Baronet — A hereditary honor title above knights but below barons. May or may not include land.
Landed Knights — Granted estates in exchange for military service.
Household Knights — Landless knights serving directly in a lord’s retinue.
Hedge Knights / Sworn Swords — Landless wanderers who sell their blades or seek fortune in tournaments.

Grand Dutchy is a sovereign territory ruled by a Grand Duke. It contains no internal Dutchy, but the rest of the feudal structure remains the same. More common then not Grand Dutchies suffer from poor economic conditions. Because of this the fall of noble houses, because of debt or internal military conflict with other nobles is not a rare sight. The Grand Dukes offer new peerage for very wealthy merchants (for coin), but more commonly for landed knights with military distinguish. Sometimes peasents are elevated to knighthood not only for military distinguish but sometimes for distinguish service to the noble house/land, and sometime even directly by the Grand Duke. The kingdoms do the same but its less common. 

On every contested border — especially those between human kingdoms — lie Marches ruled by Margraves, these are littered on the borders. These frontier lords command larger garrisons and enjoy greater autonomy due to the constant threat of invasion. The most powerful and prestigious Marches guard the demonic border.
Between the stable human kingdoms and demonic territories lies a dangerous Buffer Zone of ungoverned lands, ruined free cities with broken gates, and wild marches. This region is infested with bandits, monsters, rogue mages, and occasional demonic warbands. It serves as both a shield and a lawless frontier where fortune-seekers and exiles thrive — or die.
The border itself has been relatively calm for the past decade — one of many such “lows” that have occurred hundreds of times since the first invasions. These periods of uneasy peace are always explained by fresh infighting among the Demon Lords and Hell Princes. When one emerges dominant or a temporary truce forms in the infernal realms, raids and incursions inevitably resume.

Current Elven Realms (Present Day)
Today there is no single “Elven Empire.” Instead, there are roughly nine major High Forest Enclaves and countless smaller independent holds, plus the scattered Wildwood tribes. The largest and most influential are:

Enclave of Silverveil – The closest thing to a modern elven capital. Ruled by High Matriarch Lirael Starwhisper.
The Verdant Court of Elyndor – Known for its exceptional mages and beautiful but extremely xenophobic society.
The Moonlit Conclave – A more open-minded enclave that allows limited trade with humans and even some dwarves.
The Bloodthorn Wilds – The largest and most feared Wildwood territory.

Elven society remains highly stratified by bloodline purity and magical talent. They practice a form of feudalism blended with druidic meritocracy — noble houses rule, but a common-born elf with exceptional magical power can rise quickly. Their warriors favor elegant longbows, living blades grown from specially treated wood, and spirit-bonded animal companions.
Because elves live so long (typically 800–1,200 years, with some reaching 2,000+), they think in centuries rather than decades. This makes them slow to change but incredibly patient enemies. A grudge held by an elven house can last longer than entire human kingdoms.

The hatred between elves and demons runs deeper than any other racial enmity in Aetheria. It began during the final decades of the First Great War (around 9,000 B.S.), when the planar rifts first tore open. While the mortal races tore each other apart, the Demon Lords saw opportunity. Demonic legions poured into the material plane, drawn like vultures to the scent of spilled magic and broken ley-lines.
The Eternal Sylvandari Dominion suffered some of the worst devastation. Many of their greatest living cities — ancient forest-metropolises that had stood for millennia — were directly assaulted. Demonic corruption spread through root and soil like a black plague. Sacred World Tree offshoots were twisted into Corrupted Worldthorns, massive abominations that still bleed ichor centuries later.
The elves, with their deep connection to nature and spirit magic, were uniquely horrified by this desecration. Where other races saw territorial loss, the elves experienced the literal rape and murder of their living homeland. This created a cultural wound that has never healed.

Today, the war between elves and demons continues in a state of cold, eternal hostility with occasional flare-ups. There is no single, continuous frontline like the human-demon marches, but rather multiple dangerous flashpoints.
Active Conflict Zones:

The Blighted Reach – Largest and most infamous. A massive corrupted forest zone where High Forest Enclaves and Wildwood tribes launch regular cleansing expeditions. Demonic warbands and corrupted ent-like creatures roam here.
The Thornveil Border – Mountainous region where elven rangers and demonic sky-raiders clash regularly.
The Umbral Wilds – Southern jungles controlled partly by the Serpentis Beastkin and Wildwood Exiles. Here the fighting is especially chaotic and brutal.
The Crimson Canopy – Deep enclave territory that remains a cancerous demonic foothold. The elves have never been able to fully purge it despite centuries of effort.

Unlike the relatively calm human-demon border (which experiences decade-long lulls due to demonic infighting), the elf-demon conflict is more consistently hostile. Demon Lords who border elven lands often gain prestige by striking at the “arrogant leaf-lovers,” and certain Highblood demons (especially succubi and infernal diplomats) take particular pleasure in corrupting or breaking elven nobility.

Current Dwarven Realms (Present Day)
There is no longer a unified Dwarven Kingdom. Instead, dwarven society is organized around eight major independent Great Holds and dozens of smaller clans and colonies. The most prominent are:

Karad-Dur – The ancient capital. Still the most prestigious and powerful hold, ruled by the High King Under Stone, Thorin Ironcrown XXVII. It remains the center of traditional dwarven culture and runecraft.
Brimmbarak – The Fireforge Hold. Famous for its unmatched weapons and armor. Located near volcanic regions, its forges never sleep.
Mithralion – The richest hold, built around vast mithral and Aetherite veins. Known for master artisans and wealthy merchant clans.
Grimstone Deep – A grim, militaristic hold on the northern borders. Constantly fighting underground threats and demonic incursions.
The Wanderers of the Stone Road – Surface and semi-nomadic clans who travel between human kingdoms as master engineers, builders, and mercenaries.

Dwarven society is clan-based and deeply traditional. Status is determined by craftsmanship skill, lineage, and deeds (particularly in battle or forging). They practice a form of feudal meritocracy where even a common dwarf who creates a masterwork can rise to high status. Most dwarves live 400–650 years, with some exceptional elders reaching 800+.
Their warriors favor heavy plate armor, rune-etched weapons, crossbows, and hammers. Many still use golems and mechanical constructs in battle, though far fewer and weaker than in ancient times.

The war between dwarves and demons is older, deeper, and more bitter than most surface-dwellers realize. While the elves fought to protect their forests, the dwarves fought for the very heart of the world itself.
During the final centuries of the Great War and the immediate aftermath (around 8,900 – 8,500 B.S.), the weakening of planar barriers allowed demonic forces to pour not only onto the surface but also into the vast underground networks. The Deep Kingdom of Karadun was invaded from below as well as from above. Demons discovered that dwarven halls contained some of the richest Aetherite veins and magical forges on the planet — resources they desperately coveted.
What began as opportunistic raids quickly turned into a brutal, millennia-long underground war. Dwarves call it The War for the Root of the World. Demons simply refer to it as the Deep Harvest.

Unlike the relatively calm human-demon border or the scattered elven conflicts, the dwarven-demon war is a continuous, grinding underground war that has never truly stopped. It ebbs and flows in intensity but remains a constant drain on dwarven resources and population.
Major Active Theaters of War:

The Abyssal Deeps (Below Karad-Dur)
The most critical and dangerous zone. Located far beneath the ancient capital, these levels contain some of the richest remaining Aetherite deposits. Demonic forces maintain several fortified “Black Citadels” here. The dwarves launch near-constant reclamation campaigns. Many elite dwarven deep-delvers and golem legions rotate through this hellish front.
The Fallen Holds of Grimnarok
Once a proud sister-hold to Karad-Dur, Grimnarok fell completely during the Black Anvil era. It is now a massive demonic stronghold ruled by Duke Vorgath the Iron-Breaker, a colossal demon known for his obsidian armor and hatred of all things dwarven. The dwarves have been trying to retake it for over a thousand years with only partial success.
The Lavaforge Rift
A volcanic underground region where dwarven Brimmbarak forces clash with fire-aspected demons and magma devils. This area is strategically vital because it contains natural portals that demons use to bring reinforcements from the infernal planes. The heat and toxic gases make it a nightmare even for dwarves.
The Shadowvein Tunnels
A sprawling network of tunnels beneath the human-demon border marches. Here the fighting is more chaotic, involving dwarven expeditions, human march lords, and occasional Beastkin mercenaries. Demons use these tunnels to launch surprise surface raids.
The Lost Colonies
Scattered smaller dwarven outposts and mining colonies that were cut off centuries ago. Some still hold out as besieged fortresses. Others have gone dark — occasionally a lone survivor or a corrupted “Darksoul” dwarf emerges carrying horrifying tales.

Current Beastkin Realms (Present Day)
Today, Beastkin are widely scattered. There is no central empire. Instead, they exist as major tribal confederations, independent clans, and integrated minorities within human or elven lands. The most prominent groups include:

The Golden Pride (Lionfolk) – The most powerful and respected confederation. They control large stretches of the central savannahs and operate as a warrior-aristocracy. Ruled by the High Sun King (currently Kharak the Golden).
The Shadowpacks (Wolf, Hyena, and Pantherfolk) – Nomadic and semi-nomadic raiders and hunters known for their cunning and ferocity. They frequently clash with human border marches.
The Sky Talons (Avianfolk – Eagle, Hawk, Owl) – Masters of the high peaks and floating ruins. Many serve as elite scouts or mercenaries across the continents.
The Ironhide Clans (Bear, Rhino, and Buffalo folk) – Heavily built, fortress-dwelling tribes in the northern hills and riverlands. Renowned as unbreakable defenders and master craftsmen of bone, hide, and wood.
The Serpentis Dominion (Serpent and Lizardfolk) – A more civilized but secretive jungle empire in the southern wetlands. They practice forbidden blood rituals and maintain tense diplomatic ties with nearby demonic territories.
The Wildblood Exiles – Scattered tribes of mixed or “degenerate” bloodlines who live as bandits, gladiators, or adventurers in the lawless buffer zones.

Beastkin physiology varies greatly. Most live 80–150 years (longer than humans but far shorter than elves or dwarves), though some totemic bloodlines reach 200+. Their society blends meritocracy with tribal hierarchy — strength, wisdom, and spiritual connection to one’s totem determine status. Warriors use spears, claws, axes, and composite bows, often fighting with primal rage or totemic transformations in battle.
Magic is relatively common among them, especially Nature, Spirit, and minor Beast Transformation aptitudes. However, they rarely produce the more “civilized” schools of magic.

The war between Beastkin and demons is as old as the first infernal invasions, yet it feels more personal and visceral than the wars of other races. During the chaos following the Shattering, demonic legions poured into the open savannahs, primal jungles, and wild highlands where the Beastkin roamed freely. Unlike the dwarves (who fought in tunnels) or elves (who defended ancient forests), the Beastkin had no great walls or deep holds to retreat into. Their homelands were exposed.
Demons viewed Beastkin as particularly valuable prey — their potent blood, strong life-force, and totemic spirits made excellent fuel for corruption rituals and soul-forges. Many demonic warlords sought to twist Beastkin bloodlines into monstrous hybrid armies.
This created a deep, instinctive hatred. Beastkin refer to this conflict as The Eternal Hunt or The War of Fang and Corruption. To demons, it is simply another feeding ground.

Today, there is no single, unified war between Beastkin and demons. Instead, it is a patchwork of constant tribal skirmishes, opportunistic raids, and localized hot wars. Because Beastkin are so decentralized, the intensity of the conflict varies wildly depending on the region and the specific clans involved.
Major Active Theaters of War:

The Bloodplains (Central Savannahs)
The largest and most brutal zone. Once the heart of Beastkin civilization, this vast corrupted grassland is now a permanent battleground. The Golden Pride (Lionfolk) and allied clans regularly launch large-scale hunts here to reclaim territory and purify corrupted totems. Demonic warbands use the open terrain for fast-moving raids and chariot-like hellbeast charges.
The Umbral Wilds (Southern Jungles)
A dense, humid nightmare where the Serpentis Dominion (Serpent and Lizardfolk) and Wildwood-allied Beastkin fight a shadowy guerrilla war. This region has heavy demonic presence due to its proximity to planar rifts. Corruption spreads easily through the water and roots, creating many mutated Beastkin abominations.
The Shadowvein Border Marches
The lawless buffer zone between human kingdoms and demonic territories. Mixed Beastkin tribes (especially Shadowpacks — Wolf, Hyena, and Pantherfolk) operate here as raiders, mercenaries, and monster-hunters. Fighting is chaotic, involving ambushes, night raids, and hit-and-run tactics against demonic supply lines.
The Scarred Highlands
Northern mountainous savannahs where Ironhide Clans (Bear and Buffalo folk) maintain fortified villages. They face periodic large demonic incursions trying to break through toward human lands. These battles are the most “conventional,” featuring brutal melee clashes and siege warfare.
The Twisted Migration Routes
Ancient paths that Beastkin clans have followed for millennia. Demons deliberately corrupt these routes to disrupt Beastkin culture and force tribes into desperate situations.
